/i> ‘to stand’. However, the tradition is very confused. The name was introduced in this form to Britain by the Normans, among whom it was popular as a result of the fame of  St Eustace , a Norman nobleman who was said to have been converted to Christianity by the vision of a crucifix between the antlers of the stag he was hunting."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":20,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Eustace Le Poer was born about 1270, in Pirton, Hertfordshire, England as the son of Eustace Le Poer. He married Mrs. Eustace le Poer about 1286, in Kells, County Kilkenny, Ireland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. In 1285, at the age of 16, his occupation is listed as justice itinerant. He died in 1311, at the age of 42."},"et":{"about 1270–1311":"umbes 1270–1311","1270–1311":"1270–1311","–Female":"Surnud","–1330":"–1330","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","about 1270":"umbes 1270","after 1290":"pärast 1290","1311":"1311","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","about 1286":"umbes 1286","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","of Kells Parish, Wells, Kilkenny, Ireland":"Kells, County Kilkenny, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Pirton, Hertfordshire, England":"Pirton, Hertfordshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1270–1311":"noin 1270–1311","1270–1311":"1270–1311","–Female":"Kuollut","–1330":"–1330","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","about 1270":"noin 1270","after 1290":"1290 jälkeen","1311":"1311","1330":"1330","1285":"1285","1250":"1250","about 1286":"noin 1286","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","of Kells Parish, Wells, Kilkenny, Ireland":"Kells, County Kilkenny, Irlanti","Ireland":"Irlant